<TEXT>
musher joe runyan pulled ahead of threetime 
winner susan butcher on tuesday to take the lead in the final dash 
across the frozen bering sea to nome in the 1168mile iditarod 
trail sled dog race 
the nevana man finished the 48mile first leg of the final 171 
miles 41 minutes ahead of butcher who started the day at koyuk with 
a nineminute lead runyan and his 15dog team reached a checkpoint 
at this bering sea village at 203 pm 
butcher from manley logged in at 244 pm with 11 dogs third 
was rick swenson a fourtime iditarod winner from two rivers who 
arrived at 405 pm 
dee dee jonrowe of willow hit the trail tuesday morning two hours 
and three minutes after swenson 
the winner is expected to reach nome on wednesday morning after 
brief stops at three remaining checkpoints 
the first musher to cross the finish line on nomes historic 
front street wins 50000 the remaining 200000 is divided among 
the next 19 finishers 
with continued good weather expected the final 171 miles of the 
race across the ice of norton sound and along the hilly coastline to 
nome will boil down to speed and endurance 
all four leaders took their final mandatory rest stops monday in 
unalakleet 
although butcher has fewer dogs remaining in her team than 
runyan she said they appeared to be getting stronger 
theyre doing the butcher tricks for me she said early 
tuesday they know where they are in the race 
as of midday tuesday 41 mushers remained in the race eight have 
scratched since the race began march 4 in anchorage 
the annual race began 17 years ago and was inspired by a 1925 
relay of serum to nome during a diphtheria outbreak the race is put 
on largely by volunteers 
</TEXT>
