<TEXT>
ten states have joined a federal pilot program 
to control medical wastes but critics say it gives too little 
protection against syringes and other contaminated items washing 
onto beaches again this summer 
the environmental protection agency said monday additional 
recordkeeping requirements for medical wastes will take effect by 
this summer in states from the great lakes to the atlantic other 
states may also choose to join the program 
the pilot program was directed by congress last year after 
numerous reports of medical wastes including syringes and other 
contaminated items being found on beaches some were forced to 
close 
the program requires under the threat of civil and criminal 
penalty detailed record keeping as a particular medical waste 
travels from origination to final disposal along the way the 
transporter and others handling the waste must sign the documents 
in addition the regulation requires waste fluids and sharp objects 
such as syringes to be separated and imposes packaging and labeling 
requirements 
the record keeping covers a broad range of medical wastes such as 
human blood and blood products human pathological wastes from 
surgery and autopsies waste from patients who have been isolated 
with communicable diseases cultures and stocks of infectious 
agents and such items as scalpels needles and syringes according 
to the epa 
epa officials acknowledged that the program even if all 10 
states agree to participate is expected to address only partially 
the problem of medical wastes washing onto beaches 
many such items come from home use and illegal drug use and are 
not covered by the additional tracking requirements officials said 
the program covers wastes that originate with physicians dentists 
veterinarians small clinics laboratories and hospitals 
nevertheless said epa administrator william reilly the rules 
will substantially increase the amount of medical wastes that 
are given close scrutiny during disposal 
but a group of 19 congressmen criticized the epa for excluding 
some categories of medical wastes including items such as surgical 
gloves and bandages even if they have been used in treating patients 
with aids or other contagious diseases 
the epa cannot make the medical waste problem disappear by 
limiting the definition of the term medical waste said rep jim 
florio dnj accusing the epa of creating sweeping exemptions to 
its tracking requirements 
senior epa officials disputed claims that some medical wastes 
were excluded even though they posed health problems for example 
they suggested a rubber glove or gown may not always be subject to 
the special tracking because by the time it is in the waste cycle it 
no longer poses a health threat 
simply a waste product coming into contact with an infectious 
agent does not constitute a health risk said sylvia lowrance 
director of the epas office dealing with solid wastes 
she said that even some items that may have been in contact with 
an aids victim or a patient with a highly communicable disease such 
as hepatitis is not always considered a health threat given how 
fragile these viruses are 
the new tracking procedures will be required under a twoyear 
program in the 10 states connecticut new york new jersey 
pennsylvania ohio michigan indiana illinois wisconsin and 
minnesota other states may choose to join the program and the 
seven states other than connecticut new york and new jersey may 
withdraw from the program within 30 days 
violators in the program are subject to civil penalties of up to 
25000 a day for each violation and possible criminal prosecution 
with a maximum 50000 fine and a jail term of up to five years 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

