<TEXT>
actor and broadway producer maurice 
evans who starred in shakespeare on the london stage and later 
displayed his versatility in american television series has died in 
his native england he was 87 
evans died early sunday in the seadowns nursing home in 
rottingdean outside brighton the local coroners office said today 
cause of death is thought to be heart failure said a spokesman 
for the office speaking on condition of anonymity 
evans produced such broadway hits as teahouse of the august 
moon dial m for murder and no time for sergeants 
the naturalized american has portrayed macbeth hamlet and 
richard iii on american television but he also appeared in many 
lighter roles the puzzler on batman sir basil bertram on 
tarzan samanthas frequently absent father on bewitched 
and a french spy on daniel boone 
his film credits include rosemarys baby and the planet of 
the apes in which he played a leader of the ape planet 
he had been ill said george schaefer a longtime friend and 
dean of theater film and tv for the university of california los 
angeles 
he had a heart attack a few years back and bronchial problems 
and i guess it just all caught up with him 
schaefer called evans one of the last great actormanagers 
teahouse of the august moon earned evans a tony award in 1954 
no time for sergeants the story of a hillbilly draftee who 
nearly brings the army to its knees made actor andy griffith a star 
evans was born in dorchester his theater career began at age 7 
and his father a druggist justice of the peace and amateur actor 
cast him in adaptations of thomas hardy novels 
his big breakthrough came in journeys end in 1929 and he 
became one of londons most soughtafter stage actors but he 
continued to run a drycleaning business during the day once 
saying i have no intentions of winding up starving in an attic 
he joined the old vic theater in 1934 and portrayed such 
classical shakespearean roles as hamlet caesar and petruchio he 
also favored bernard shaw plays performing in saint joan and 
major barbara 
with his smooth baritone voice he was lured to broadway in 1935 
for romeo and juliet 
he became an american citizen in 1941 and entered the army in 
1942 staging about 60 plays for us troops including a popular 
shortened version of hamlet that became known as gi hamlet 
he rose to the rank of major and headed the army entertainment 
section in the central pacific in world war ii 
after the war he returned to broadway becoming a critical 
success and a millionaire he had been in semiretirement for the 
past 10 years 
evans had no immediate survivors funeral services were to be 
held wednesday at a local crematorium 
</TEXT>
