bartenders mixed singapore slings by the dozen 
today as visitors savored a last taste of the old orient before 
raffles hotel closed for a twoyear renovation 
the hotel established in 1886 was the social center for the 
grand and the beautiful when this southeast asian island was a 
british colony the raffles guests once included such writers as 
somerset maugham rudyard kipling and joseph conrad 
maugham said raffles stands for all the fables of the exotic 
east kipling advised eating there but sleeping elsewhere he said 
the beds were uncomfortable 
visitors today thronged the hotels bar where the singapore 
sling was invented 74 years ago others wandered around the 
groundfloor lobbies and shops where sadfaced staff sold tshirts 
coffee mugs and other souvenirs of raffles final hours 
the 127room hotel was to close at midnight for renovation of the 
building and construction of an extension at a cost of 78 million 
it is to reopen in 1991 as a luxury hotel to compete with the 
skyscraper hotels that have opened in recent years renovators also 
plan to retain raffles oldworld features 
the hotel owner dbs land ltd is an arm of development bank 
singapore of which the singapore government owns a majority 
the threestory hotel is named after sir stamford raffles a 19th 
century british official of the east india co he is regarded as the 
founder of colonial singapore 
during the japanese occupation from 1942 to 1945 the hotel is 
reputed to have been the center of the japanese secret police the 
kempeitai 
british colonial officials returned after the war to patronize 
raffles after singapore became independent in 1965 the hotel still 
had a magnetic draw for those who wanted to taste the orient 
the posh new hotels in the city offer much more comfort and 
service but lack the charm of raffles which relies on high 
ceilings and whirring fans to dispel singapores equatorial heat 
air conditioning was installed in the guest rooms some years ago 
but it threw out all the atmosphere recalled mike gallagher of 
