<TEXT>
a pharmaceutical company today said drugresistant 
strains of the aids virus have been found in patients undergoing 
longterm treatment with the firms azt drug 
wellcome plc was confirming a report in todays wall street 
journal the newspaper said the finding could lead some doctors to 
use the wellcome drug more selectively or in combination with other 
drugs for treating acquired immune deficiency syndrome 
azt is the only drug approved by the us food and drug 
administration for treatment of aids 
wellcome said the resistant viral strains were found in 
laboratory analyses of samples taken from aids patients showing 
severe symptoms of the deadly disease there were no significant 
changes in the condition of these patients at the time the 
drugresistant viral strains were observed it said 
it said the information does not require alterations in patient 
therapy or the conduct of continuing clinical trials but stressed 
that the responsibility for treating those infected the aids virus 
lies with the physician 
the british pharmaceuticals company said reviews of the data by 
its own scientists and by a panel of aids experts have been 
submitted for publication in the us journal science 
wellcome shares fell 36 cents to 784 with the announcement 
they then recovered to 813 
jonathan de pass a pharmaceutical analyst at barclays de zoete 
wedd ltd said the discovery of drugresistant hiv strains was no 
major surprise as the aids virus is known to be prone to rapid 
mutations 
de pass also said he did not expect the discovery to have a major 
impact on azt sales because of the drugs known toxic sideeffects 
doctors already were expected to prescribe azt in progressively 
lower doses and in combination with other drugs he said 
didier cowling an analyst at nomura research institute said the 
major danger to azt sales could come if the fda were to block any 
application by wellcome to use azt as a treatment for socalled 
asymptomatic carriers of hiv those who do not yet show any 
symptoms of the aids disease 
wellcome is testing the possible benefits of azt on asymptomatic 
patients and cowling expects the first results of these tests to be 
available by the end of this year 
aids is caused by the hiv virus which damages the bodys immune 
system leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer 
it is spread most often through sexual contact needles or 
syringes shared by drug abusers infected blood or blood products 
and from pregnant women to their offspring 
