<TEXT>
a firefighters union and a furniture 
manaufacturers trade association said tuesday they have agreed to 
support californias strict proposed public furniture fire 
resistance test for adoption in all states 
adoption of the test could raise the manufacturing cost of sofas 
and chairs by 20 percent but save thousands of lives by the end of 
the 1990s said the international association of fire fighters and 
the american furniture manufacturers assocation 
the standard would apply only to furniture used in public areas 
such as hotel lobbies day care centers jails and the like and not 
in hotel rooms or private homes 
we had to crawl before we could walk we want to see the effect 
of this said alfred k whitehead president of the union in 
explaining why the two organizations were limiting the coverage of 
their proposal 
the california standard has been proposed by that states bureau 
of home furnishings but is not in effect there yet however some 
california cities have adopted it locally 
the test calls for placing five sheets of newspaper in a 
specified open steel box on the seat of the item being tested 
igniting the paper and monitoring the test chamber to see that 
temperature rise smoke density carbon monoxide concentration and 
weight loss from the test item do not exceed specified levels for an 
hour and a half 
the aim is to delay the onset of flashover the sudden 
ignition of the entire room and the combustible gases it contains 
given off by the burning item 
furniture passing the test will at a minimum slow the spread 
of fire in these occupancies allowing firefighters to save more of 
the occupants from death or injury whitehead said 
the test is many times more stringent than current industry 
standards for resistance to cigarette ignition which accounts for 
75 percent to 80 percent of furniturerelated fires said les flippo 
of the associations upholstered furniture action council 
no furniture meets it today except for costly specially 
made items said flippo whose association members account for 80 
percent of the industry 
