<TEXT>
for 23 years from a site high above waimea 
canyon ron chen has helped nasa monitor americas manned 
spaceflights 
but this week he and about 70 coworkers are tracking the mission 
that will cost them their jobs 
the kokee tracking station is scheduled to close at the end of 
the fiscal year on sept 30 it is one of six nasa ground stations 
being put out of business at a savings of 36 million a year by 
mondays successful launching from the shuttle discovery of the 
latest tracking data and relay satellite tdrs for short 
the kicker is that we are helping to put it tdrs in 
position said chen who as telemetry supervisor processes all the 
information coming down from the shuttle 
the satellite joins one fully functioning and one backup tdrs in 
orbit 22300 miles above the earth to complete a network that relays 
radio communications between shuttles and the earth during 85 
percent of each orbit 
using ground stations radio contact is possible only when the 
shuttle is roughly above each station a total of about 15 percent 
of each orbit 
chen thinks closing the station is a mistake because of the 
chance one of the new satellites could fail nasa plans to launch a 
fourth tdrs as further backup late in 1990 
weve known for a long time that this place would be closing 
its no surprise said station manager dan funamura we were 
supposed to have closed 10 years ago 
many of the employees have been at kokee for 20 years or more and 
have established roots here 
most have been offered positions by bendix field engineering co 
which operates the station for nasa but most want to remain on 
kauai funamura said 
sometimes i want to go with the company other times i want to 
stay here said les sueyasu operations supervisor who is the 
stations voice in communications with nasa headquarters in 
houston and the goddard space flight center in maryland 
right now im going to stay here said sueyasu a native of 
kauai who has been at kokee since 1964 
funamura a kauai native who has been at the station since it 
opened in 1960 also plans to stay 
but job opportunities on the island for skilled technicians are 
limited he said 
its going to be strange going out into the streets looking for 
a job said ed edwards computer systems supervisor who has been 
at the station since it opened i am real attached to the place 
and am married to a local girl so my roots are here 
the station which has supported every us manned space flight 
except the suborbital mercury flights is on a 25acre site at an 
elevation of 4200 feet in kokee state park overlooking waimea 
canyon the canyon is a popular attraction on the west side of kauai 
island about 100 miles northwest of honolulu 
most of the site will be returned to the state a small section 
will be turned over to the navy which has radar and telemetry 
facilities there 
chen points with pride to several important contributions the 
station has made to the manned space flights 
we were the first station to detect the electrical problem 
which caused the thrusters to keep firing during the gemini 8 
mission he said the problem cut short the march 1966 mission 
kokee also is one of only three tracking stations capable of 
processing live television from the shuttles and usually is the 
first to receive video from space chen said 
we remote it to houston which makes it available to the 
networks he said 
john glenns first manned orbital flight in february 1966 is the 
most memorable space mission for funamura 
we practiced for weeks and when the actual thing came it was 
tremendous he said 
other stations scheduled for closing because of tdrs are at 
ascension island in the south atlantic santiago chile guam 
dakar senegal and yarragadee australia they employ a total of 
nearly 400 people 
