<TEXT>
washingtons worst outbreak of meningococcal 
disease in more than a decade has caused four deaths this year and 
has health officials considering a costly countywide vaccination 
program 
seventeen people have contracted some form of meningococcal 
disease including six who got meningitis inflammation of the 
membranes that envelop the brain and the spinal cord 
people are freaking out about this all over said marcy 
smith whose 2yearold daughter was one of about 400 people 
vaccinated monday the shots went primarily to children in this 
yakima indian reservation town of 3300 about eight miles south of 
yakima 
i think we are on top of the current cases yakima county 
health director dr bob atwood said as the battle against the 
disease intensified he said officials knew of no other suspected 
cases im not willing to predict there wont be another case 
he said 
fighting the disease has cost the county 30000 to buy vaccine 
and an asyet uncalculated amount in overtime pay for employees 
working 16hour days if the health department decides on a 
countywide vaccination program the cost of medical supplies is 
estimated at 356000 health officials said 
county commissioners said they planned to inform gov booth 
gardners office tuesday about the costs and were considering 
whether to ask for emergency state assistance said sylvia hinojosa 
of the commission office 
the state department of social and health services has alerted 
other counties to be on the lookout for any increase in 
meningococcal disease but knows of none outside yakima county said 
dr nancy snapp 
seventy to 80 cases of meningococcal disease are reported in the 
state each year and the yakima outbreak is the largest since 1978 
officials have said 
the dead include three children under age 1 and a 23yearold 
yakima man 
in selah an apple country suburb north of yakima where the 17th 
case was confirmed over the weekend in an infant 2400 
schoolchildren were given notices to report to a school to be 
interviewed by health workers and if necessary receive either the 
vaccine or rifampin which kills the meningococcal germs in the nose 
and throat and thus halts the spread of the disease 
we identified five children playing with the infant on a daily 
basis atwood said 
the disease is primarily passed through coughing and other 
contact with secretions from the nose and throat atwood said 
the health director has come under fire for a decision to 
withhold information about the outbreak from the public until 
reporters found out about it late last week 
noting the disease has all the symptoms of the common cold 
atwood said he feared anxious parents would overload medical 
facilities and delay health care for the truly sick emergency rooms 
were flooded by concerned parents over the weekend he said 
meningococcal disease usually has a mortality rate of 10 percent 
while the yakima outbreak is running at nearly 25 percent 
officials have contacted the federal centers for disease control 
in atlanta to help determine why this outbreak which is of the 
lesscommon type c strain of the disease is so dangerous 
