<TEXT>
the conservative government set aside its 
taxreforming zeal tuesday and unveiled a budget more cautious than 
expected underscoring its commitment to combat inflation with high 
interest rates 
chancellor of the exchequer nigel lawson announced in the house 
of commons the government will leave income tax rates unchanged in 
the fiscal year beginning april 1 
he also projected a 24 billion surplus much larger than 
expected 
provided we stand firm on our resolves against inflation the 
prospects before us are excellent lawson said 
neil kinnock leader of the opposition labor party condemned the 
budget as a botched attempt to make up for the chancellors 
excesses and messes of last year 
last march lawson slashed britains income tax rates by cutting 
the top band from 60 percent to 40 percent and reducing the basic 
rate from 27 percent to 25 percent 
the cuts spurred britains strong spending boom and worsened its 
trade deficit which widened to 363 billion in january from 304 
billion in december 
inflation increased from an annual rate of 33 percent to 75 
percent 
this prompted prime minister margaret thatchers government to 
push the commercial banks base interest rates to 13 percent from a 
low of 75 percent in june 
economists were expecting lawson to tread carefully tuesday and 
he was more restrained than expected 
the budget requires approval from parliament which is assured by 
the conservative partys large majority 
under britains budgetary process the chancellor announces how 
the government will raise revenue in his spring statement in an 
autumn statement he details the spending plans 
lawson said he would raise in line with inflation allowances on 
personal income taxes and the thresholds at which taxpayers begin 
making payments 
market forecasts had called for these limits to be increased at a 
rate significantly higher than inflation 
lawson also eased the burden on employees for contributions to 
national insurance which pays for social services and simplified 
the system in addition he eased taxes on small businesses 
investors in socalled personal equity plans which invest in british 
stocks and on unleaded gasoline but he increased taxes on company 
cars 
the tax measures will reduce revenue in fiscal 1990 by less than 
34 billion the chancellor said 
he said britain will have a budget surplus of 24 billion in the 
new year matching its surplus in the current year forecasts had 
predicted the surplus would be about 52 billion 
lawson said he expects britains economic growth to slow to 25 
percent this year following 45 percent growth in 1988 
he said some slowdown in growth is inevitable as we get 
inflation back onto a downward path indeed it has almost certainly 
already begun to happen 
lawson said he expects the annual inflation rate to increase to 8 
percent over the next few months then fall to 55 percent by the 
fourth quarter and to 45 percent in the second quarter of 1990 
interest rates will stay as is needed or as long as is needed 
for there will be no letting up on our determination to get on top 
of inflation lawson said 
however unwelcome high interest rates must be they are 
preferable to the damage done by high inflation lawson said 
