the government adopted a rule tuesday that will 
require foreign airlines operating in the united states to have 
security programs approved by the federal aviation administration 
transportation secretary samuel k skinner told the senate 
transportation appropriations subcommittee that the new requirement 
is aimed at making sure foreign carriers have adequate security 
measures to protect civil aviation against criminal acts of 
violence 
the rule was proposed by the government late last year before 
the dec 21 destruction of pan american flight 103 by a bomb over 
lockerbie scotland which resulted in 270 deaths 
american carriers are already required to have faaapproved 
security procedures 
under the new regulation the 111 foreign airlines serving the 
united states would have to submit their security procedures to the 
faa within 90 days of the rules official publication in the federal 
register that is expected thursday 
the faa is required to tell the carriers if their rules are 
adequate within 30 days of receiving them if they are judged 
insufficient the government could ultimately withdraw an airlines 
permission to land in this country 
each carriers security program will be required to be in place 
within 180 days of the new rules publication 
