<TEXT>
individuals have easy access to credit and 
business has big profits to use so the 76monthold economic 
expansion an oldtimer by most standards is springing forward 
like an upstart 
the economys strength which might even be growing continues in 
spite of efforts by the federal reserve to restrain economic 
activity through higher interest rates and in defiance of repeated 
forecasts of an imminent slowdown 
the level of activity has spread doubt among forecasters 
forecasts of a slower economy are just that forecasts says j 
patrick bradley of pnc financial corp we must admit few signs of 
a slower economy can be found 
among the latest reports of economic strength is an updated 
survey by the national federation of independent business that shows 
small business optimism in february was the highest for that month 
in four years 
the survey based on an opinion sampling of the federations 
500000plus business members shows companies are able to withstand 
higher interest rates by financing internally through profits rather 
than by borrowing from banks 
remarkable profit gains continue to keep regular borrowing 
activity at nearrecord low levels said survey founder william 
dunkelberg economist and dean of temple universitys school of 
business 
dunkelberg points out that smaller businesses are aware of rising 
interest rates and clearly expect financing to become more difficult 
and expensive but for the time being have been shielded from 
creditrestraint efforts 
a vaguely similar thesis has been offered to explain the 
continued use of increasingly costly credit by consumers credit is 
so available according to the thesis that the temptation to borrow 
is much stronger than a decade ago 
perhaps the most significant of consumer credit changes is 
development of the home equity loan which often carries with it a 
tax deduction for interest paid moreover housing inflation has 
made relatively large sums available 
whatever the reason the university of michigans consumer 
sentiment index made up of attitudes toward existing and 
anticipated economic conditions rose strongly from december to 
january 
in the business sector dunkelberg termed the optimism 
surprisingly strong 
twentytwo percent of respondents to the smallbusiness survey 
agreed in february that now is a good time to expand up from 16 
percent a year earlier only 12 percent thought the economy would 
weaken while 24 percent indicated they expected it to improve 
these figures represent a substantial turnaround in the outlook 
for the economy he said adding significantly 
in spite of the unprecedented length of the recovery the 
outlook is for further improvements in the economy rather than a 
leveling of economic activity or a recession 
that optimism was reflected in plans to build inventories which 
the 15yearold survey showed were at record highs for the month 
and in hiring plans and job openings which reached a fouryear high 
dunkelberg said that although plans to raise prices continued to 
fall from the expansion high reached in december 1988 when 32 
percent of all respondents had such plans the percentage reporting 
actual price increases continued to rise 
planned or unplanned he said this translates into higher 
inflation rates 
</TEXT>
