<TEXT>
the radioactive steam that escaped during 
the neardisaster at the three mile island power plant has long 
since dissipated but debate over the health effects of the accident 
has not 
countless pieces of data have been collected about the physical 
and psychological symptoms of nearby residents animal maladies 
plant abnormalities and other problems that might be attributed to 
radiation 
industry officials government agencies and residents have 
conducted scores of surveys and studies on the radiations effects 
the state health and agriculture departments said their studies 
found no evidence that reported animal and plant problems were due 
to the accident the plants owner general public utilities corp 
said its studies showed not enough radiation was released to cause 
the described symptoms 
marjorie and norman aamodt who lived about 50 miles from the 
plant listened to the troubles of residents for years in 1984 
they decided to survey neighborhoods close to three mile island 
about symptoms and said they found cancer deaths of up to seven 
times greater than expected 
general public utilities and the nuclear regulatory commission 
covered up the enormous suffering of people who were exposed to 
intense plumes of radiation mrs aamodt said 
the state health department disputes their contention 
dr george tokuhata director of epidemiology for the department 
has overseen about 25 studies on the effects of radiation that 
escaped mostly xenon and krypton gases and a very small quantity of 
iodine 
i do not think their worries are warranted although there are 
some disagreements about the amount of radiation released he 
said our studies show radiation release was very low 
state researchers estimate that people within fives of the plant 
were exposed to 5 to 80 millirem of radiation depending on how 
close the radioactive plumes passed on the average the areas 
residents are exposed to about 100 millirem of naturally occurring 
background radiation each year tokuhata said 
if you had 10 millirem its a fraction of one chest xray 
he said so you really do not expect a major significant health 
impact from that 
tokuhata said the main effect of the accident has been on the 
psychological wellbeing of residents 
extra medications taken by pregnant women at the time of 
the accident impacted on low birth weight babies he said that 
risk was significantly greater among those women who took extra 
medications compared to those who did not 
dr gordon macleod who took the job of state secretary of health 
just 12 days before the accident agreed that the main health 
effects appeared to be psychological ones that resulted in higher 
alcohol and drug use by residents as well as increased anxiety 
macleod however also conducted research that concluded an 
abnormally large number of babies were born with thyroid problems 
after the accident 
but macleod who is now professor of public health and clinical 
professor of medicine at the university of pittsburgh said he 
believes data will not be able to show whether radiation caused 
increased incidents of cancer or other conditions because of a 
multitude of other factors that could contribute to such diseases 
more than 2000 damage suits have been filed against general 
public utilities or the plants builders a 25 million agreement 
was reached in one class action suit filed shortly after the 
accident including 5 million to underwrite health studies 
in 1985 insurance companies representing the utility agreed to a 
1 million payment for a downs syndrome child born nine months 
after the accident and 855000 for a child who suffered cerebral 
palsy the agreements specified that the decision to settle was 
merely economic and that the children did not suffer any provable 
injuries as a result of radiation from the accident 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

