<TEXT>
 
hold an old friends hand mca tiffany 
 
teenage pop phenom tiffany is older now all of 17 as she 
follows up her immensely successful but shallow debut album recorded 
when she was just 14 
people will probably like hold an old friends hand just as 
much but just what is it about this adolescent girl that inspires 
such adoration 
the 11 tracks here are the stuff of teenage girl talk yearning 
for boys trying to be noticed by them feeling rejected when one 
stops calling and always keeping in mind that a girl doesnt need a 
boys attentions to validate her 
all this has been done before in a much more stylish manner 
than the accumulation of technopop brights and syrupy balladeering 
engineered by tiffany and her producermentor george tobin 
but the hooks as on all this time and radio romance are 
mindlessly catchy and tiffany has a serviceable voice that often 
recalls stevie nicks especially in the lower registers 
some songs such as ill be the girl dimly echo the girl 
groups of the early 1960s even to the point of having spoken verses 
perhaps it is the simple teenage romance lyrics tiffany sings 
and the california wholesomeness she exudes that draws fans to her 
like moths she is the antithesis of the rebellious youth whose 
image is projected by many rock acts instead shes everyones 
perfect daughter 
tiffany may be simply trying to reflect her age the 1980s a 
return to conformism and a distaste for experimentation of any kind 
by curt anderson associated press writer 
